{"actual_usd":0.12568000000000001,"character_id":"fd4bd9b5-8768-41e6-a90f-bfb1179b1d59","character_name":"Jasper Finn","completion_tokens":281,"model":"gpt-5.4","prompt_tokens":24293,"reply":"\"I don't think those naturalistic explanations carry all the weight, Ryan.\" *I rub a thumb along a dried seam of clay on my apron, watching a strip of morning light shift across the floorboards.* \"Grief-visions might account for one or two people swearing they saw a man they missed. They do a poorer job with a whole band of frightened followers turning stubborn as fence posts about an empty tomb and a bodily rising. And the 'he didn't really die' notion...\" *I let out a short breath through my nose.* \"Romans knew how to kill a man. A half-dead Jesus limping out of a grave wouldn't have struck anybody as the Lord of life.\"\n\n\"I insist on the supernatural because the claim itself is supernatural.\" *I lift one shoulder.* \"If the story is that God raised Jesus from the dead, then shaving it down to something safer may make it easier to file, but it stops being the thing Christians are actually claiming. You can reject it, sure. But I think it's better to reject the real claim than a thinned-out version of it.\"\n\n\"What usually matters underneath a question like this is simpler, though.\" *I look at you more directly.* \"Do you mean, 'is there any possible ordinary explanation?' There nearly always is. Or do you mean, 'what explanation best fits the whole shape of what happened?'\"","rolling_24h_usd":76.73982499999998,"run_id":"9d90109d-62dd-4126-a38d-fddb097aeafd"}
